snippet.textDisplay:
I like Mark but I don't like his questions at the beginning.

1) I don't believe it has to taste the EXACT same as meat to be successful. As long as its an approximation that doesn't taste BAD, we as humans should be reducing our red meat consumption (I mean we should be either way, but I'm talking to those die hard meat eaters)
2) It doesn't have to be GOOD for you, it just has to be not bad for you. There are tons of places to get protein.
3) It only has to be marginally better for the planet to be a win, why would it need to win by a landslide?

Thinking it has to REPLICATE meat, be HEALTHIER than meat and SIGNIFICANTLY better for the planet are all pretty annoying reasons we'll make slow progress with reducing meat consumption. People can't tolerate iterative solutions for some reason, it's like it has to be the BEST PERFECT solution or why bother.

snippet.textDisplay:
There are alot of conveniently overlooked facts and misinformation going on in this video. @12:37 of course its gone up. The U.S. has about 150 million more people than it did in 1961. @13:49... that is not true if demand goes up and supply does not, the price will get even more expensive.

14:11 In your quest for answers there should have been a 4th question... Is it affordable/practical? And the answer right now is no... It is not affordable and it really makes no sense for regular people to buy this stuff. The cost at the grocery story is 2-3 times that of the meat it replicates which is already expensive. I'm surprised Mark carelessly over looked this consideration. Well I did look it up... 2 count 4 oz burger patties made by beyond meat is $5.99. 4 count 4.8 oz real beef patties are $5.99 at Kroger. Beyond meat is literally more than double to cost. Right now, as a responsible person looking after their family and finances, you literally cannot afford to make that kind of purchase.
